                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d462">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">White</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1903-01-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 10, 1903</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Mr. Hay states that Mr. Bowen will leave Caracas for Washington on January 11;
                    that he is anxious for the raising of the blockade at the earliest possible
                    moment on account of scarcity of provisions in Venezuela threatening general
                    distress. Mr. Hay has answered Mr. Bowen that no preliminaries can be adjusted
                    before his arrival, and that the raising of the blockade may depend on the
                    sufficiency of the guarantee.</p>
                <p>Mr. White is directed to suggest to the British minister for foreign affairs that
                    the matter might be taken into consideration with a view to early
                    determination.)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
